segments.text: First of all, Mr. Badgett, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, if you know them, the places of their birth, the place and date of your birth, and schools which you attended before you came to Texas A&M.
I was born in Denison, Texas, which is in Grayson County.
near what is now the...
In 1906, December 1st, 1906, my father was Walter Alexander Batchelor, born in Grayson County near Hector, Texas, which is near Whiteride.
Am I speaking loud enough?
My mother was also born in that area, Margate Alice Blanton,
My grandfather, her father, and mother had migrated to Texas in the covered wagon train immediately after the Civil War from the Carolinas.
I graduated from the Denison High School in 1924.
Following that time, I spent a year at Austin College, which is in Sherman.
about eight or nine miles from my home, commuting most of the time in urban, which was in use in those days, from Denison to Dallas and Waco.
After a year there, taking a liberal arts course, I came to Texas A&M.
What type of business was your father in, or what was his occupation?
My father was a general building contractor in Denison, in that area, for quite a number of years.
I don't remember, probably 40 years or something of that sort.
He died during the war, at which time my two brothers were both overseas, one of them with patents on him and one of them with the 7th Army in northern New York.
My mother's still alive.
She is 92 years old now.
She's still living in Denison?
She is still living in Denison.
My sister, who is the next youngest child of me in the family at 65 now, just retired and lives with my mother.
What factors were involved in your change from, say, Austin College Liberal Arts to Texas A&M?
I guess I probably went to Austin College because of its nearness and the fact that I had a scholarship there when I entered.
And during that time, I believe it was January 19 and 23,

I came to A&M for Texas, State Texas Older Boys Conference and spent several days here and was very favorably impressed with the college and having worked with my father in the construction business, I naturally had some feeling for looking toward architecture.
And that is why I came here in the fall of 19 and 25.

graduating with a BS in architecture on the mechanical structural end in 19 and 29, followed by work on a master's degree in architecture that year, but didn't complete my thesis and get my degree until 19 and 32.
In the meantime, I was working with the college architect
In fact, I guess that may be of some interest how I came to work at A&M.
Okay.
Could we step back a minute on something else first?
Sure.
How were you, you entered A&M then as a sophomore?
No.
No?
You had to enter as a fish?
I had to enter as a freshman, changed into engineering, and taken military too.
I restricted the transfer of credits that I could use on my architectural degree.
In fact, I only got credit for English.
The others were not applicable to the engineering course.
So you did have to go through the whole freshman year.
I was a freshman after I had met a slime, they called him up at Austin College at the time.
What were your first reactions to the school?
Of course, you had been here once before, or at least once, but not as a student.
I presume it was somewhat different when you came as a student.
Well, at the time I came down here, of course, there were not many highways.
At that time, the Southern Pacific ran several trains, passenger trains, through College Station.
I had left Denison on the Southern Pacific train to Dallas, where I transferred.
That was in the afternoon.
And in Dallas I ran into a chap named Rayford Lance from Sherman, who was a sophomore, to be a sophomore at A&M.
And we transferred to the, what was then called the Owl, a midnight train from
left Dallas about 11.30, arriving at college at 4.30 in the morning.
We got off the train in a rain at 4.30 in the morning.
And of course, it was pretty dark around there then.
And we carried our handbags.
Of course, we had trunks, so we had to get later.
Handbag up to the campus.
Lance having been here a year, we rustled around and found an empty bed on the bottom floor of Leggett Hall and spent the rest of the night there.
And then of course that day was registration day and one of the questions then, well what outfit are you going to be in?
What military science are you going to take?
What company are you going to get in?
And I had met some other prospective freshmen during the early morning, and we agreed we would get in some company if we could.
I don't remember that now, but I wound up in A Infantry because the company we had planned to get in was full at the time.
And fortunately continued living like it was.
The infantry was in Leggett that year and back in there my junior year.
My sophomore year we had, I always thought the fortunate thing of being able to live in what was called Hollywood Shacks.
That was an interesting place for anyone but a freshman.
We had running wood and water and of course the freshmen ran after the wood and we ran after the water and the toilets were in a common latrine over

On the side of these shacks, I think there were about 130 of them, about 16 by 16 square, and there must have been an acre of cordwood sawed and stacked up there because your house was heated with a wood stove.
How many students assigned to a shack?
Three.
There were room, usually you stacked two cots,
One of them, there could be four in there.
It was a fairly good sized room, approximately 16 by 16.
And three could live in there comfortably.
And we, being sophomores, had lots of fun there.
Of course, it was right convenient for people to drown out others, because usually your bed was in front of a window.
There were three windows and a door in the room.
During the night, you may get a GI can of water thrown in through the window on you.

Another common fun thing was while the students were out in the mess hall for evening meal, someone might plug your stovepipe and put sulfur or something else on your stove, which made it rather untenable to live in for a while afterwards.
I could imagine that it would.
Wasn't burning of sulfur commonly used for bedbugs?
No, well, just somebody getting some powdered sulfur or something that would stink and smoke up the room.
I haven't stopped up your chimney, too, your stovepipe.
So you got both the sulfur and the smoke.
We lived right by the shack I was in, I think it was 102, and it was right beside the Tunerville Trolley, which in those days ran from
College Station to Bryan at what I thought was the best example of motion going in all directions at once of anything you could find.
In fact, I've even got nauseated or motion sickness from riding it from Bryan to College Station after having dinner occasionally in town on Saturday night.
You said you lived in the Hollywood Shacks for only one year.
Well, those times your outfits rotated around.
It didn't always stay in the same dormitories every year.
For how long were the Hollywood Shacks there, do you remember?
When I came down here first for this older boys' conference in 1924, I think it was January 24,
At that time they had tents.
These were out in front of the YMCA building where Law and Pereer Hall are now located.

They had a wooden deck floor and then a pyramidal tent and the students lived in those tents which at the time I was down here it snowed and I guess rather uncomfortable in a tent in the wintertime in the snow.
But by the time I had come back the following year they had built
a hundred some odd of these Hollywood shacks, we called them, out there where the tents were.
These stayed in that location until Law and Prayer Hall were erected, which would be 1926, I believe, and started in 1927.
And that area and what they did is simply moved them on back further toward the railroad track and what is now the parking lot beside Law and Career Hall.
Where they were continued to be used as dormitory rooms.
They were used as dormitory rooms.
I don't remember when we discontinued them now.
They were sold off and floated all over
Rises County people have brought them up because they're a nice little house.
I've been told that there's still some in existence in a few places.
There were a few on the campus till not very many years ago that were used for storage sheds.
In fact, Cashin Cabin down in Hensel Park is composed of three of those cabins that were put together to make one house.
It originally was down in

where a lake was in the horticulture farm area just west of the railroad and when they built the ag engineering building or the greenhouses, the first time this cabin was moved down to Hensel Park, used as a recreational area for quite a number of years and still is in existence there now.
You mentioned that you lived in Leggett as a fish and as a junior.
Where did you live as a senior?
As a senior, I lived in the north corner on the third floor of Mitchell Hall.
I remember the rooms in Leggett Hall, 51 my freshman year and 55 my junior year.
I don't know what the number was, didn't make a difference, but I lived in the only
actually the third floor, with Richard Akers, who graduated with me.
You mentioned that in the Hollywood shacks it was fairly convenient for drowning out at night or stuffing up the stove.
What was life like in the main dormitories?
I would imagine it would be a little bit more difficult or complicated for drowning out, and of course, stuffing up the stovepipe was not a possibility there.
In Leggett Hall, we slept in three bunks strapped to each other, one above the other.
My first three years in A&M, I had two roommates.
One was Carol Dautre from Houston and Johnny Yonick from Weimar.
Yonick died during the war.
The fellow who drew the top bunk
In the wintertime, never had to have any cover.
We had radiators in the room, and of course the higher up you got near the ceiling, the warmer it was.
So it got pretty warm up there in the winter.
Now going back to the shacks, for a moment, the wood stoves we had in there made awfully nice places to have a weenie roast or do some other cooking that you might improvise

on a cold winter evening, but I guess one of the big differences was of course you had a company usually had a floor and maybe part of another and two floors, but at that time it was common practice for any upperclassman who wanted any errand run or any work done for him to stick his head out the door and holler freshman.
and all the freshmen on the floor had to break their neck getting there because the last one there was the one who got the chore.
So sometimes it got to be quite a rat race, students making their way to the, trying to get there first rather than last.
And there was no way of knowing in advance what the responsibility might be.
And of course most
In the dormitories, in the shacks, the freshman students always had the job of cleaning up the upperclassmen's room.
You were usually assigned to some upperclassmen's room, and that was your chore to make up the beds, change the linen, and sweep the floors, and wash the basin, what have you.
This was always an unofficial responsibility, though.
Well, yeah, but you knew what your job was.
After you became an upperclassman, I assume then you had a choice of who would be your fish?
Normally you did, yes.
Where one freshman didn't have too many rooms, they used enough freshmen to go around and keep it up.
Of course, there were some rooms that freshmen
detested very much having to clean up because naturally some people aren't as neat and clean as others.
But there was not necessarily a rotation.
No, you might keep your assignment for the semester.
Sometimes it would change, but there was no real method about it.
What about the food that was served to you in a mess hall?

uh pretty good or did you have a lot of complaints about it well it was my observation that there was hardly a freshman who came here i'm speaking particularly the freshman now who didn't gain weight that year of course this was due to two things probably a regularity of work and sleep and meals plus meal hounding it was called then
At the tables, you were seated by companies, as I guess it's done now in Duncan Hall.
But it was your job to seat the upperclassmen.
We're fed first, and then if anything was left, you might fill up on gunwadding and regulator.
Regulator, it was molasses, and of course gunwadding was bread.
And crews from table to table to find something was left over to fill up.
And a lot of them, a lot of students had made quite a fetish out of trying to bring things out of the mess hall.
Of course, they had an army sergeant stationed at each door to try to check people to keep them from carrying off all the silverware in China and food.
But they were very innovative.
methods that were worked up to get out with a pie, or maybe it was bread and molasses, or whatever they might find they want to bring up.
And particularly, the freshmen had the job of bringing food out to some of the upperclassmen who didn't like to get up on Sunday morning and go down for breakfast.
So on Sunday morning, and you weren't required.
Sunday morning breakfast was voluntary, no formation.
Every other day it was by formation.
By formation you fell in and then marched to the dining hall.
Usually at retreat in the spring and the fall we had retreat formation with a band playing and the cadet corps marching in.
The military walk was a military walk in those days.
It was closed off to vehicular traffic and
During the week, you marched from wherever your dormitory was down the Military Walk to Speza Hall.
On Sunday morning, you marched the other way to Guyon Hall for Compulsory Chapel.
I think one of the most embarrassing occurrences my senior year, my organization at that time,
formed in front of Leggett Hall between Leggett and Mitchell, down in that area, and we were the first outfit to march in the dining hall.
On Sunday nights, well, half of Brian, it seemed, came out to watch the cadet corps parade in the dining hall.
I was a cadet staff officer in the
I remember the first Sunday evening it came my lot to take the cadet corps to the dining hall after retreat.
I was down just in front of the dining hall and of course was facing the organizations and giving some commands and then did an about face to march off.
Well, we wore boots as they do now and spurs.
And somehow or another when I did my about face and had my feet together and then stepped off, my feet didn't go with me.
I went but my feet didn't.
My spurs got hung together and locked and I fell flat before all the crowd out there in front of the dining hall.
I would imagine that would be a rather embarrassing situation.
At the time when you were a student, did you have a guard mount in the evening during the quiet hour?
No, we didn't have a guard mount, but you had called quarters and the senior company commander or his assistant, it was his job to see that you didn't roam around and

and visit, and if you left during call to quarters, which I believe was between 7.30 and 10.30 or 10.45, you were not to leave the dormitory or rooms unless you got permission and then you had to post notice on your door where you had gone and when you'd be back.
But there was no one walking guard to her to see that you were there.
But the matter of posting a notice was for all classes, not just the freshmen?
I don't remember that it applied particularly to the upper class when they had, of course, a little more freedom than the freshmen.
But the regular guard mount had been discontinued some years before I came.
You mentioned the fact that perhaps the upperclassmen had more freedom than the freshmen as far as moving around the dormitory at night and not having to post a notice of where they were.
What other privileges did upperclassmen have?
I think we talked earlier about the upperclassmen were fed.
They got the first choice of the meal at the mess hall.
Of course, they got there.
rooms clean.
I don't know of any particular ones.

Passes to leave the campus were a little more lenient, but if you weren't 21, you still were supposed to either get an individual or a standing permit, one from your parents, to authorize you to leave the campus.
to go anywhere other than Bryan or College Station, of course.
Well, College Station wasn't here then.
A large number of the staff and faculty lived on the campus.
It seemed like we had somewhere around 250, 300 faculty houses altogether, both on the campus and some off on the farms.

In fact, the block that the Student Center occupies now was completely filled with faculty, cottages, and all down from that block, well, where the new athletic dormitory is just finished, was houses.
Raleigh White Coliseum is on both sides of that.
And then, of course, behind Guyon Hall on the side of the present Tower Center now.
And on down what was called Quality Row.
That's a street that goes down now past the President's House and
General Ludeke lives.
This was called Quality Row because on that street the heads of departments and directors and some of the deans lived.
Was that the street where those original brick houses?
The original brick houses were on the side of the park alongside just west of the dormitories, the 12 dormitories.
And I believe there were also some faculty houses over where the USDA
That's right.
The area that the, what we called then the four dormitories, at one time were 14, 15, 16, 17.
And where the USDA building is now, 500-inch staff houses occupied that area.
And then on up where the more recent dormitories were built there,
I'm not familiar with the names of those now.
Between there and the U.S. Post Office were houses, and then there was old Alpha and Beta Hall, which were two-story frame buildings where the casuals lived.
We called the students who were not taking military science, either been in World War I or were physically disabled or were rather old,
not taking military science, and then the Cadet Corps were called casuals, and they lived in those buildings.
And then in 19, what, 26th, I forget the year now, the Aggieland Inn was constructed on the site of these.
And for many years,
was the only state owned hotel in the United States.
Used to be quite a center for food, coffee, and a two dollar room.
Somewhere in our picture file, we have a picture of a Shirley Hotel, which was considerably earlier.
Do you know where that was?
Yes, the Shirley Hotel was just opposite the
Board of Directors' quarters.

At that time there was a road that curved off of Houston Street about the Board of Directors' room and went on down to one of the north gates where the interurban from, or Tunerville Trolley we always called it, the interurban from Bryan College Station left the campus or entered the campus.
And then beside the street and the track there was what was Postgraduate Hall, PG Hall, where graduate students lived.
And across the street from that was the old bachelor's quarters, which I lived in for a year after I graduated.
But there were many occupants left around here that John Paul happened to work with.
Yeah, I see.
Duke Thornton lived in Batchelor Quarters, Batchelor Hall.
He was the head of me there.
He married at that time.
Let's see.
There was T.R.
Spence, with whom I had the pleasure of working a number of years when he was
manager of construction for the A&M system, was born on the campus.
And I believe one of the houses, I mean that Dean Spence lived on the site I believe of the student center.
And I believe Guy Adrens was born on the campus too.
